  "text": "Kubernetes RBAC authorization implementation consists of several interconnected components in the kubernetes/kubernetes repository:\n\n**Authorization Engine:**\nThe RBACAuthorizer (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/rbac.go) implements the core authorization logic with the Authorize method that evaluates whether a user request is allowed. It uses a RequestToRuleMapper interface to obtain policy rules for a user, then checks each rule using RuleAllows() to determine if the request matches any allowed policy rule.\n\n**Rule Resolution:**\nThe DefaultRuleResolver (pkg/registry/rbac/validation/rule.go) is the primary implementation of the RequestToRuleMapper interface. It resolves PolicyRules for a given user by:\n1. Collecting all applicable ClusterRoleBindings via ListClusterRoleBindings()\n2. Collecting all applicable RoleBindings in the target namespace via ListRoleBindings()\n3. For each binding whose subjects match the user, resolving the referenced Role or ClusterRole via GetRoleReferenceRules()\n4. Accumulating all matching rules and returning them through RulesFor() and VisitRulesFor() methods\n\n**Subject Evaluation:**\nThe SubjectAccessEvaluator (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/subject_locator.go) implements the SubjectLocator interface to provide the reverse lookup - determining which subjects can perform a given action. It traverses all RoleBindings and ClusterRoleBindings to identify subjects whose rules allow a particular operation.\n\n**REST Handlers:**\nMultiple REST handlers in pkg/registry/authorization/ expose the authorization engine:\n- SubjectAccessReview (subjectaccessreview/rest.go): Evaluates if a specific subject can perform an action\n- LocalSubjectAccessReview (localsubjectaccessreview/rest.go): Namespace-scoped version of SubjectAccessReview\n- SelfSubjectAccessReview (selfsubjectaccessreview/rest.go): Allows users to check their own permissions\n- SelfSubjectRulesReview (selfsubjectrulesreview/rest.go): Returns all rules applicable to the current user\n- Authorization storage (rest/storage_authorization.go): Coordinates the REST endpoints with the authorizer\n\n**Bootstrap Policies:**\nThe bootstrappolicy package (plugin/pkg/auth/authorizer/rbac/bootstrappolicy/) defines initial RBAC policies that are created during cluster initialization:\n- policy.go: Contains core ClusterRoles and ClusterRoleBindings with standard verbs (Read, Write, ReadWrite) and metadata labels\n- controller_policy.go: Defines ClusterRoles for system controllers with the \"system:controller:\" prefix\n- namespace_policy.go: Defines Roles that are bootstrapped into reserved kube-* namespaces\n\n**Escalation Prevention:**\nThe policy-based storage implementations enforce privilege escalation prevention:\n- escalation_check.go: Provides utility functions (EscalationAllowed, RoleEscalationAuthorized, BindingAuthorized) to check authorization before allowing escalation\n- role/policybased/storage.go: Wraps Role storage to prevent users from creating/updating Roles with permissions they don't possess\n- clusterrole/policybased/storage.go: Wraps ClusterRole storage with similar escalation prevention, using fullAuthority (permissions to do anything) as the upper bound\n- rolebinding/policybased/storage.go: Prevents users from binding Roles they cannot escalate (either by explicit escalate permission or by already having all the role's permissions)\n- clusterrolebinding/policybased/storage.go: Applies the same escalation prevention for ClusterRoleBinding operations\nAll these storage implementations call ConfirmNoEscalation() in the DefaultRuleResolver to verify that the user's current permissions cover all permissions they're trying to grant.\n\n**Helper Utilities:**\n- helpers.go (pkg/registry/rbac/): Provides IsOnlyMutatingGCFields() to distinguish policy changes from garbage collection metadata updates\n- helpers.go (pkg/registry/authorization/util/): Provides ResourceAttributesFrom() and NonResourceAttributesFrom() to convert SubjectAccessReview specs into authorizer.AttributesRecord for evaluation"
